Handling Null Values

There are several ways to handle null values in a dataset.

Fill in the missing values with the median value of each column.

diabetes_median <- diabetes %>%
mutate_all(~ ifelse(is.na(.), median(., na.rm = TRUE), .))

fill in the missing values with the mean value of each column

diabetes_mean <- diabetes %>%
mutate_all(~ ifelse(is.na(.), mean(., na.rm = TRUE), .))

fill in the missing values with the common value of each column


fill_mode <- function(x) {
  mode_val <- names(sort(table(x), decreasing = TRUE))[1] 
  x[is.na(x)] <- mode_val 
  return(x)
}

diabetes_mode <- diabetes %>%
mutate_all(fill_mode)

Handling Outliers

Z-score (z-score standardization) is a method for handling outliers. It is calculated using the following formula:

\[ Z = \frac{{X - \bar{X}}}{{\sigma}} \]

where:

  • \(X\) is the specific value.

  • \(\bar{X}\) is the mean of the variable.

  • \(\sigma\) is the standard deviation of the variable.

This method helps standardize the data and identify values that deviate significantly from the mean.

diabetes_z <- (diabetes - colMeans(diabetes)) / apply(diabetes, 2, sd)
diabetes_z
NA

Drawing scatter plot from the graph


melted_diabetes <- gather(diabetes_z, key = "Variable", value = "Z-score")

# V scatter plot cho tt c cc ct
ggplot(melted_diabetes, aes(x = Variable, y = `Z-score`, color = `Z-score`)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Variable", y = "Z-score", title = "Scatter Plots of Z-scores") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))  # iu chnh gc v v tr ca ch thch trn trc x

Drawing scatter plot from the graph, we observe that values >= 700 are outliers

# Lc cc gi tr Z-score m tt c u nh hn 360
diabetes_filter <- diabetes[rowSums(apply(diabetes_z, 2, function(x) abs(x) < 700)) == ncol(diabetes_z), ]

# Hin th kch thc ca b d liu sau khi loi b
cat("Cn li s lng hng v ct l:", dim(diabetes_filter))
Cn li s lng hng v ct l: 760 9

  • m bo rng cc bin c thang o ng nht, gip m hnh hc tt hn.

  • Gim nh hng ca bin ln gia cc bin.

  • Ph hp vi cc m hnh yu cu d liu nm trong khong gi tr c th .

\[ \text{Scaled Value} = \frac{{\text{max}(X) - \text{min}(X)}}{{X - \text{min}(X)}}\]

min_max_scaler <- function(x) {
  return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

diabetes_scale <- as.data.frame(lapply(diabetes_filter, min_max_scaler))
diabetes_scale
NA

PREDICTING DIABETES using Logarithmic Regression model

train <- diabetes_scale [1:530,]

model <-glm(Outcome ~.,family=binomial(link='logit'),data=train)
summary(model)

Ba thuc tnh ph hp nht, Glucose, BMI v Mang thai c gi tr p thp, cho thy mc ngha cao. iu ny cho thy rng cc bin c lp ny nh hng ng k n hiu sut ca m hnh hi quy logistic trong d on Kt qu.

###Cross Validation

Bt u nhn dng v chuyn i xc sut thnh nhn d on 1: mc bnh ,0: khng mc bnh Tnh ton ma trn nhm ln 

fitted.results <- predict(model,newdata=test,type='response')
fitted.results <- ifelse(fitted.results > 0.5,1,0)
(conf_matrix_logi<-table(fitted.results, test$Outcome))

Tnh ton chnh xc ton th, nhy, c hiu

TP <- conf_matrix_logi[2, 2]  # True Positive
TN <- conf_matrix_logi[1, 1]  # True Negative
FP <- conf_matrix_logi[1, 2]  # False Positive
FN <- conf_matrix_logi[2, 1]  # False Negative

Accuracy<-(TP+TN)/(TP+TN+FP+FN)
cat(" chnh xc:",Accuracy,"\n")

#trong s bnh nhn thc t b bnh tiu ng,bao nhiu phn trm c d bo b bnh
Sensitivity<-TP/(TP+FN)
cat(" nhy:",Sensitivity,"\n")
#trong s bnh nhn thc t khng b bnh, bao nhiu phn trm c d bo khng b bnh

Specificity<-TN/(TN+FP)
cat(" c hiu",Specificity)

Classifying the categories of Mass (BMI)

The World Health Organization (WHO) classifies adults based on the following BMI ranges:

  • Underweight: < 18.5 kg/m^2

  • Normal weight: 18.5 - 24.9 kg/m^2

  • Overweight: 25.0 - 29.9 kg/m^2

  • Obese: 30.0 kg/m^2

library(ggplot2)
diabetes_filter$BMI_Category <- cut(diabetes_filter$BMI, 
                             breaks = c(-Inf, 18.5, 24.9, 29.9, Inf), 
                             labels = c("Underweight", "Normal", "Overweight", "Obese"))

Trc quan phn b ca tng loi cn nng

ggplot(diabetes_filter, aes(x = BMI_Category)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "count") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of BMI Categories", x = "BMI Category", y = "Count") +
  theme_bw()

# Lp li qu trnh hun luyn v nh gi trn cc gi tr khc nhau ca ntree
error_out_of_bag <- c()
error_test <- c()
for (ntree in 1:100) {
    # Hun luyn m hnh
    model <- randomForest(BMI_Category ~ . -DiabetesPedigreeFunction -Age -Outcome -Pregnancies, data = train, ntree = ntree, mtry=3)

    # Tnh li ra ngoi ti
    error_out_of_bag[ntree] <- mean(predict(model, train) != train$BMI_Category)

    # Tnh li kim tra
    error_test[ntree] <- mean(predict(model, test) != test$BMI_Category)
}

# V ng cong li
plot(error_out_of_bag, type = "l", col = "blue", ylab = "OOB error", xlab="S cy trong rng")
lines(error_test, type = "l", col = "red")

Cch 1: One-Sample T-test

###gi thuyt BMI (Ch s khi c th) trung bnh 31 d mc bnh tiu ng

# V biu  histogram
ggplot(diabetes, aes(x = BMI)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, fill = "lightblue", color = "black") + 
  labs(x = "BMI", title = "Histogram of BMI") + theme_minimal() 

# summary statistics
kable(summary(select(diabetes, BMI)), format = "markdown")

###gi thuyt BMI trung bnh mc bnh tiu ng l 31

\[ H_0: bmi = 31 \] \[ H_a: bmi \neq 31 \]

t.test(diabetes$BMI, mu=31)

Kt lun v gii thch

  • T u ra v t p.value chng ta thy rng
  • p-value nh mc ngha 5%.
  • Ging nh bt k bi kim tra thng k no khc , nu p-value nh hn mc ngha th c th bc b gi thuyt. > Da vo kt qu kim nh t-test, c th kt lun rng gi tr trung bnh thc s ca ct BMI khng bng 31, v c lng trung bnh ca mu c th nm trong khong t 31.43410 n 32.55106 vi mc tin cy 95%.

-

Cch 2: Independent Samples T-test

chng minh phn trm m trong c th cng nh hng n vic c mc bnh hay khng

gi thuyt lng m trong c th (BMI) khng nh hng n vic c bnh hay khng

# V biu  histogram
ggplot(diabetes, aes(x = BMI_Category)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "count") + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of BMI Categories", x = "BMI Category", y = "Count") + 
  theme_bw()

###gi thuyt t l BMI ca ngi bnh v khng bnh l nh nhau \[ H_0: bmi_0 = bmi_1 \] \[ H_a: bmi_0 \neq bmi_1 \]

#ly ra nhng ngi bnh v khng bnh c ch s BMI_Category >= 3
sick <- num_diabetes[num_diabetes$Outcome==1 & num_diabetes$BMI_Category >= 3,10]
normal <- num_diabetes[num_diabetes$Outcome==0 & num_diabetes$BMI_Category >= 3,10]

t.test(normal,sick,var.equal=FALSE)

Kt lun v gii thch

  • T u ra v t p.value chng ta thy rng
  • p-value nh mc ngha 5%.
  • Ging nh bt k bi kim tra thng k no khc , nu p-value nh hn mc ngha th c th bc b gi thuyt. > Da vo kt qu kim nh t-test, c th kt lun rng lng m trong c th c nh hng n vic ngi c bnh tiu ng .

chng minh tui cng nh hng n vic ngi c b bnh tiu ng hay khng.

gi thuyt tui trung bnh mc bnh tiu ng l 32
